Character(2B): 
All programming languages that follow the ASCII table usually store each character in 1 byte (8 bits). That means one character takes 1 byte of memory.
However, Java does not follow ASCII. It follows Unicode, so in Java each character (char data type) uses 2 bytes (16 bits) of memory. 
Because of this, Java can support a much larger number of characters compared to ASCII-based languages.

