    }
}
public class First {
    int x, y;
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        First t1 = new First();
        System.out.println(t1.x);// Here we get def value provided by JVM which is 0 
        t1.x = 100;// updating value from 0 to 100
        System.out.println(t1.x);// here we het 100
    }
}

2. Static/class level variables: Values doesn't varies from object to object, Common for all objects.
By default value(0) provided bu JVM, loades when class load, Lifecycle(static var) = Lifecycle(class), Load inside method area.
Declare inside the class but outside all the blocks with static keyword. Accessible by (reference variable, class name and directly)
public class First {
    static int x;
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        First t1 = new First();
        First t2 = new First();
        System.out.println(x);//Direct access
        t1.x = 100;
        System.out.println(t2.x);//100 (By reference access)
        System.out.println(First.x );//100 (By class name)
    }
}
Best way to access static variables is by class name.

3. Local/temporary/stack/automatic variable: Declare inside the block(block maybe method, constructor or any other)
when these blocks loades into the memory at that time local variables also load automatically into the memory. Store inside the stack area.
These variables do not have their default values by JVM, not even garbage, we have to assign their default values. Their is no garbage value concept in java.
