When we press Enter to run a Java program, some processing happens before we get the output.
1. JVM start.
2. JVM create a thread named 'main-thread'.
3. main thread load the class in method area.
4. Execute main method(PSVM), then main method print the output.
Now, after execution of whole main method
5. class unload.
6. main thread destroyed.
7. JVM shutdown.
So, when program is in running state it is called thread(main), process.

var-arg mehod(JDK 1.5V): Accept 'n' number of arguments.
Syntax(void function_name(data type ...
var-arg: variable no. of argument method
public class First {
    public static void m1(int... x) {// (...) is ellipse operator
        System.out.println(1);
    }
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        m1(null);
        m1(10);
        m1(10, 20);
        m1(10, 20, 30);
    }
}
This ellipse/var-arg method implements array internally, that is why it accepts n no. of arguments.
Prove of the above statemtnt:
public class First {
